Magic: The Gathering EDA

Josh Folsom

Data Exploration of MTG Data Set

This report explores a dataset containing a variety of attributes for approximately 39,000 Magic: The Gathering Cards

Data from https://github.com/yhejazi/mtg-web-scraper thanks to Yasmine Hejazi
Description stored in MTGPackage

Univariate Exploration

The first thing I wanted to do was load in my dataset, and then check the attributes this dataset included, so I could get an idea of where I would like to explore. Though some of these are fairly self-explanatory a few others were just abstract enough that I wanted to get a better footing before diving in. One thing I do notice immediately that has me slightly concerned is the max value of 1,000,000 in convertedMana.

Out of curiousity I grabbed a sampling of cards that appeared more than once in the dataset
These are filtered by x > 1,x > 5, and x > 10
Typically they would appear more than once if they were released in a different set, I was impressed to see that over 200 cards have seen more than 10 appearances. Because of the large amount of duplicates I will need to be cognizant of performance impacts as well as whether I consider duplicates to be a valid(or invalidating) factor on my analyses.

Because I wanted to see the shape of the data by Converted Mana Cost (CMC) I created a simple histogram with CMC limited to an upper bound of 20

I also want to see the spread of cards by rarity

Bivariate Exploration

My first exploration of two variables was converted mana cost faceted on card type to see where the bulk of my data fell

 

From that histogram I can see there are a few very sparse cardtypes. I may roll them into some of the more popularly occuring types

 

I created a bar graph, scaled logarithmically, to see what sort of shape emerged, or more importantly how much variance in converted cost there was, by type

Coverted Mana Cost Density by Rarity

 

I then did a density check by rarity, which uncovered 3 groups I didn’t want to use in this dataset: Bonus, Promo, and Special

I think that some more valuable observations can be made by expanding back out of the sample, and searching for some other observations from the whole subtype data column, SO I did a check for the Mean CMC as well as the count of each Subtype with various levels of strictness for minimum subtype counts

I also decided to go back and added median as a measured variable. The Last graph shows just how effective that was, which makes sense, certainly; with some subtypes having hundreds of results though a .98 correlation was a little surprising.

Reflection

This dataset was nearly 40,000 cards, Spanning almost 30 years that the game has existed. My goals at the onset were to find some trends based on my own experiences with the game. the two largest were relations between Rarity and CMC, and the general cost trends by subtype. Some of my attempts were ridiculously unsuccessful, resulting in datasets of 0, or in one case 55 million, which I didn’t see as practical.
R feels like a powerful (and quick) tool that gives its users a great handful of approaches to the same problem; In my case that was more of a burden than a boon as I never felt like I’d analyzed my dataset in the ‘best’ way.
I Was hoping to create buckets that contained multiple matching values (subtypes appearing more than once if they matched the stripped down, single word subtypes). I’ll need to perform further research on my own time.
I would have liked a year-released column, as that would have provided some interesting insights for which card subtypes had the greatest longevity. Having the artist for the cards would be neat too, to determine who Wizards of the Coast used most often.
